=========================================
C++11 TRAILING RETURN TYPE (INTERVIEW NOTES)
=========================================

What is trailing return type?
-----------------------------
A trailing return type allows specifying the return type
AFTER the function parameters using -> syntax.

Syntax:
-------
auto functionName(parameters) -> return_type;

-----------------------------------------
Basic Example:
-----------------------------------------

#include <iostream>

auto add(int a, int b) -> int {
    return a + b;
}

int main() {
    std::cout << add(5, 3);
}

Output: 8

=========================================
WHY USE TRAILING RETURN TYPE?
=========================================

1. Readability for complex return types
----------------------------------------

auto getPair() -> std::pair<int, double> {
    return {42, 3.14};
}

Useful when return type is long or complex.

-----------------------------------------
2. Return type depends on parameters (IMPORTANT)
-----------------------------------------------

template <typename T1, typename T2>
auto multiply(T1 a, T2 b) -> decltype(a * b) {
    return a * b;
}

✔ decltype ensures correct return type
✔ based on expression (a * b)

-----------------------------------------
3. Needed when return type uses parameters
------------------------------------------
Before C++14, parameters are not visible before return type,
so trailing return type is required.

=========================================
WHY IT WORKS (IMPORTANT CONCEPT)
=========================================

Function parameters are NOT available before return type.
So this fails in C++11:

❌ auto add(T a, T b); // return type not known early

Trailing return fixes this:
✔ auto add(T a, T b) -> decltype(a + b);

=========================================
FUNCTION POINTER CASE
=========================================

using FuncPtr = auto(*)(int, int) -> int;

Used in advanced generic programming.

=========================================
C++14 IMPROVEMENT
=========================================

From C++14 onwards:

auto add(int a, int b) {
    return a + b;
}

✔ Compiler automatically deduces return type
✔ No need for trailing return type in simple cases

=========================================
WHEN TO USE TRAILING RETURN TYPE?
=========================================

Use when:
✔ Return type depends on template parameters
✔ Using decltype expressions
✔ Complex/long return types
✔ Pre-C++14 codebases

Avoid when:
✘ Simple functions (use auto in C++14+)

=========================================
INTERVIEW ONE-LINER
=========================================

Trailing return type in C++11 allows specifying the return type
after the parameter list using ->, useful when return type depends
on template parameters or decltype expressions.

=========================================
QUICK REVISION
=========================================

- Syntax: auto f() -> return_type
- Used in C++11 templates
- Helps with decltype return types
- Required before C++14 for dependent return types
- Replaced by simple auto return in C++14+
